trans-unit.source: You can use the <ui>Join</ui> module to perform a join operation on two tables.
trans-unit.target: You can use the <ui>Join</ui> module to perform a join operation on two tables.

trans-unit.source: The module supports the following join types:
trans-unit.target: The module supports the following join types:

trans-unit.source: An <newTerm>inner join</newTerm> is the typical join operation.
trans-unit.target: An <newTerm>inner join</newTerm> is the typical join operation.

trans-unit.source: It returns the combined rows only when the values of the key columns match.
trans-unit.target: It returns the combined rows only when the values of the key columns match.

trans-unit.source: A <newTerm>left outer join</newTerm> returns joined rows for all rows from the left table.
trans-unit.target: A <newTerm>left outer join</newTerm> returns joined rows for all rows from the left table.

trans-unit.source: When a row in the left table has no matching rows in the right table, the returned row contains missing values for all columns that come from the right table unless you specify a replacement value for missing values.
trans-unit.target: When a row in the left table has no matching rows in the right table, the returned row contains missing values for all columns that come from the right table unless you specify a replacement value for missing values.

trans-unit.source: A <newTerm>full outer join</newTerm> returns all rows from the left table (<ui>table1</ui>) and from the right table (<ui>table2</ui>).
trans-unit.target: A <newTerm>full outer join</newTerm> returns all rows from the left table (<ui>table1</ui>) and from the right table (<ui>table2</ui>).

trans-unit.source: For each of the rows in the left table that have no matching rows in the right table, the join results include a row containing missing values from the right table.
trans-unit.target: For each of the rows in the left table that have no matching rows in the right table, the join results include a row containing missing values from the right table.

trans-unit.source: For each of the rows in the right table that have no matching rows in the left table, the join results include a row containing missing values for all columns from the left table.
trans-unit.target: For each of the rows in the right table that have no matching rows in the left table, the join results include a row containing missing values for all columns from the left table.

trans-unit.source: A <newTerm>left semi-join</newTerm> returns only the values from the left table when the values of the key columns match.
trans-unit.target: A <newTerm>left semi-join</newTerm> returns only the values from the left table when the values of the key columns match.

trans-unit.source: To perform a join on two datasets, they must be related by a single key column.
trans-unit.target: To perform a join on two datasets, they must be related by a single key column.

trans-unit.source: The combined dataset cannot have two columns with the same name.
trans-unit.target: The combined dataset cannot have two columns with the same name.

trans-unit.source: Therefore, if the left and right datasets have any duplicate column names, a numeric suffix is appended to the column names of the right dataset to make them unique.
trans-unit.target: Therefore, if the left and right datasets have any duplicate column names, a numeric suffix is appended to the column names of the right dataset to make them unique.

trans-unit.source: For example, if both datasets had a column named Month, the column from the left dataset would remain as is, and the column from the right dataset would be renamed Month (1).
trans-unit.target: For example, if both datasets had a column named Month, the column from the left dataset would remain as is, and the column from the right dataset would be renamed Month (1).

trans-unit.source: The algorithm that is used for comparison of key values is hash-forced.
trans-unit.target: The algorithm that is used for comparison of key values is hash-forced.

trans-unit.source: Each column of the joined dataset preserves a categorical type, if the corresponding column of the input dataset is categorical.
trans-unit.target: Each column of the joined dataset preserves a categorical type, if the corresponding column of the input dataset is categorical.

trans-unit.source: In left outer joins, if there are any missing values, a categorical level is created in the left dataset for missing values.
trans-unit.target: In left outer joins, if there are any missing values, a categorical level is created in the left dataset for missing values.

trans-unit.source: This is true even if there are no missing values in the joined (right) dataset.
trans-unit.target: This is true even if there are no missing values in the joined (right) dataset.
